english:
  title: A Letter to Hwangbo Yaksoo
  author: Im Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I write to you upon hearing from a man lately arrived from the capital, who says the examination system shall surely be reformed, and attributes this first to your efforts. If indeed this is so, it is truly a matter for celebration. How could I not have foreseen it? I merely rejoice that it accords with my long-held hopes.

    In recent times, the selection of scholars has been bound by the rules of prosody, so that mere children often pass the highest grades, while truly learned men are cast aside. Both court and countryside have mourned this injustice. I feared this affliction had taken root too deeply to be corrected in a day, yet now we have gained you. Though I dwell in a distant place and cannot judge all that follows, the nation has indeed found a worthy man.

    You, the son of a celebrated father, have brought great honor to your house. Your learning is profound, your accomplishments refined, and your years still young. You shall soon wash your head in the very clouds and cast your light across the rainbow—ascending to the constellation of literary stars and entering the imperial halls as swiftly as dawn or dusk. Like one climbing a ladder who rises higher with each step while all below gaze upward, such is your ascent. Could any but the heir of generations of literary excellence achieve this?

    I, meanwhile, have been broken and cast down, made a laughingstock of the world. Confined to a remote village, I grow only more ignorant and narrow. My learning does not increase, my path does not advance—I have become merely an ordinary man. In writing, one must work through vital force, yet after traversing so many sorrows, my spirit has grown desolate. I am now but a weary farmer. When I read these days, I wish only not to forget the Way of the sages. Should I somehow gain a second chance to sit for the examinations and serve at court, I am already old and could accomplish nothing. What grieves me is that my family has long been known for its literary arts, and should I abandon myself in foreign lands without continuing this legacy, it would be a shame I could not bear in all my remaining days.

    Yet is it not destiny that has brought me here? Thus I have given my heart to mountains and streams, holding no desire for worldly affairs. I spend my time with hunters and fishermen, wandering the waters and hills without constraint or ceremony. This suffices to leave me without regret. Since recent years, those with whom I once shared fellowship have nearly all faded away, which brings me sorrow. Yet my body remains sound, and I have reached this day. Should I die in such contentment, it would be a blessing. What matter then are glory and shame?

    Moreover, having offended the world through my frank wildness, those who bark against me multiply like dogs. Would they find satisfaction in my ruin if I did not bear such hardship? Therefore I embrace it as sweetly as honey. I observe that among the gentlemen of our age, few harbor great and distant ambitions. Most merely use the examination system as a means to wealth and rank. But as for one who flows like rain and strides like thunder, walking boldly through the halls of letters to revive the literary spirit of the Western Han—who but you?

    Strive! Strive! The two pieces I send reflect where my heart truly dwells. I write this to you with sincere respect.
  footnotes:
    - The Western Han is referenced here as the golden age of Chinese literature and culture, representing a standard of excellence the author hopes the recipient will help restore.
    - The 'vital force' (氣) mentioned here refers to the qi or spiritual energy that classical Chinese aesthetics held as essential to all great writing.
